    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. But some people argue that substantive due process is basically just judicial activism and that the court shouldn't be making up \"rights\" that aren't explicitly in the Constitution. Can you add a part to the explanation that shows why their view is considered a more legally sound approach to the Constitution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that substantive due process amounts to judicial activism because it allows unelected judges to impose their own policy preferences onto the law, rather than interpreting clear constitutional text. This view champions a more text-based approach, asserting that rights must be explicitly enumerated in the Constitution to be enforceable. Proponents of this view fear that relying on implied rights allows the judiciary to become an overly powerful, subjective lawmaker. This perspective insists that democracy demands that fundamental rights be democratically debated, not judicially invented.",
      "source": "target",
